the normal range of motion of the tongue is as follows:

  * protrusion: the tip of the tongue should be able to extend forward beyond the lower front teeth.
  * lateral excursion: the tongue should be able to move laterally to touch the inside of the cheek on either side.
  * upright position: the tongue should rest comfortably behind the lower front teeth when the mouth is closed.
  * depression: the tongue should be able to move downward toward the floor of the mouth.
  * elevation: the tongue should be able to move upward toward the palate.
  * rotation: the tongue should be able to rotate clockwise and counterclockwise.

it's important to note that some variations in the range of motion can occur due to individual differences and certain medical conditions. if you have concerns about your tongue mobility, consult with a healthcare professional.

the normal range of motion of the tongue is as follows:

  * protrusion: the tongue should be able to protrude straight out of the mouth without deviation to one side or the other.
  * lateral excursion: the tongue should be able to move laterally to touch the inside of each cheek.
  * upright position: the tongue should rest comfortably in the mouth with the tip of the tongue touching the bottom teeth behind the front teeth.
  * suprahyoid elevation: the tongue should be able to elevate up towards the hard palate.
  * depression: the tongue should be able to lower down towards the floor of the mouth.
  * rotation: the tongue should be able to rotate clockwise and counterclockwise.

it's important to note that the range of motion of the tongue can vary depending on the individual and their specific anatomy. additionally, certain medical conditions or injuries may affect the mobility of the tongue.

the procedure for complete dissection of the sylvian dissection complex procedure (sdcp) based on the sylvian fissure morphology involves starting the dissection from the distal part of the anterior sylvian point (asp) and releasing the deep cisternal part in advance. the dissection should then be performed step by step from the distal to the proximal part. the key step is to completely dissect between the opercular gyrus (og) and the posterior surface of the pyramidal process (pp), as insufficient dissection of these structures can make it difficult to release their proximal part due to tight adhesion.

  1. midpoint of the lower lip on either side
  2. one-third to one-half of the distance from the corner of the mouth to the chin on either side
  3. the point where the nasolabial fold meets the vermilion border of the upper lip on either side
  4. directly above the mental protuberance, in the midline of the chin

it's important to note that injection techniques may vary depending on individual anatomy, treatment goals, and practitioner preference. it is always best to consult with a qualified healthcare professional for personalized advice and treatment recommendations.
